comments.text: I did get this to print: Had to download as an OBJ and imported it into 3D Studio Max. Then I used the editable mesh modifier and used the select face setting to remove the spindly legs on the bottom of the building. I had to get rid of these because the 3d Printer was having lots of trouble placing single dabs of filament on top of each other. This was causing the extruder to become completely covered in a big bundle of filament, making it impossible to continue... so I just got rid of them. Then you have to export the file from 3DS Max as an OBJ and import that back into MakerBot Desktop and print that from there. I suggest printing with a raft so as to get a bigger base.

description.text: Trianglesssssssssss!

Bonjour,

L'idée de ce projet est de fabriquer une planche de Paddle avec une imprimante 3D, 2 ou 3 composants facile à trouver et quelques notion de bricolage.

Ce premier prototype est un échec...

Je vous déconseille fortement d'essayer de réaliser cette planche. chaque pièce demande entre 18 et 24h d'impression et le résultat n'est pas toujours au rendez vous. Pour une planche de 2m, il faut conter pas loin de 80 pièces ce qui représente environ 20 bobines de 1Kg de fil ABS.
Le prix moyen d'une de ces planches dans le commerce (en France) est de 400€ à 500€ soit à peu pret le coup de ce prototype.

Je ne baisse pas les bras pour autant, je travail sur un nouveau proto !!

Je donnerai des nouvelles ASAP.

By

Prototype 1 : échec...

Pour ce premier prototype, il faut 4 éléments :

  • une imprimante 3D (beaucoup de bobine de file ABS)
  • des bouteilles d'eau de 50cl vide avec leur bouchon
  • des manches à balai (5)
  • de la corde élastique (16-20m)

Les bouteilles d'eau vide servent de flotteurs. Elles sont inséré dans les trous de Ø62mm.

Les 5 manches à balai servent de structure à la planche. Notez qu'il est nécessaire d'ajuster leur taille afin de rendre l'assemblage possible.

La corde quant à elle sert de lacet. Elle traverse toute la planche et vient serrer toutes les pièces les une contre les autres.

I wanted a better system than the block of wood to cool the filament when it leaves the Filastruder.
This is my First Design but I am working on several more.

This design (FCS) allows for customization according to your needs. It utilizes one or two 60mmX10mm fans. If you choose one fan, you can pick which dirrection the air flows. If you use two fans, the wires can be run through the small hole as to not get in the way when both fans are wired together. The FCS also has a 8mm shaft hole to add a roller(s) at the end. I use several skateboard bearings on a carbon fiber shaft because I had them on hand. You could use two bearings wrapped in copper, aluminum or ?
The mounting screw holes are offset so it can be mounted with roller end hanging off the end of your Filastruder baseplate. I placed the open areas on the bottom to help control warping on the printbed and to save filament. I designed this using Fusion360, the file can be provided if needed.
If you find the FCS useful or have a suggestion, please comment. I ask at some point in the future that you help out a fellow Veteran by saying "Thank You for Serving" or something of your choosing.

The several design found on Thingiverse weren't up to my taste. I wanted something:

  • Adjustable
  • Not colliding with other pegs (remember: a ukulele is small)
  • Not too ugly

Great sound by the way!
I've printed mine in ABS, but PLA works just as well.
If you find ABS too slippery, some talc powder makes wonder.
25 to 33% infill seems to be enough, but be sure to have 4 shells at least.

Once printed, insert in the ukulele and put the cord into first hole then directly into the next hole (a quarter turn) and so forth until you got it secured (it took me 4 passages to do so, YMMV).
To help you tune, you can also take advantage of the several iphone, android and even windows phone Ukulele tuner out there!
Happy playing...

3DPrint.com article: http://3dprint.com/79580/3d-printed-pop-pop-boat/

The boat is powered by steam, using a candle to boil water in a “boiler.” The water boils, thus expanding into steam, and this expanded steam pushes water that is in the exhaust (plastic straws), causing the boat to move about the water. Then when the water cools down, it creates a vacuum which sucks more water into the exhaust, thus creating a cycle that repeats itself. While this process is occurring there is a very clear popping sound created, thus the name “Pop Pop Boat” is quite fitting.

description.text:
Got my Printrbot Play today and it worked brilliantly, except the cable to the print head kept snagging on the printbed. It gets caught behind it, stopping the bed moving back (or snapping loose with a lot of force). I was worried about it breaking the motor or belt.

I designed this to clip on the Z-motor and secure it with a tie wrap, the cable itself is redirected up and sideways. The cable can be secured with 2 smaller tie wraps.

Please note it was a really quick 15-minute so there are some rough edges. But it's a functional part so I didn't really care :) It prints well with grid support in Cura which is hard to remove afterwards. Didn't try it with lines support yet.

I just thought I'd put it on here in case anyone else has the same problem (maybe not all printers do)

This is an unapproved mod so try at your own risk!
